<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-china">
  <title>Ancient Chinese Mathematics (5.3, 5.5)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-The-Nine-Chapters">
    <title>The Nine Chapters</title>

    <p>
        With thousands of years of continuous civilization, China is one of the world's oldest cultures. Chinese history can be divided into 3 broad periods: Ancient (8500 - 221 B.C.), Imperial (221 B.C. - 1912 A.D) and modern (1912- ). Many different dynasties have rule over parts of China over the years. Some of the most important ones are the Shang (1600-1046 B.C.), Han (202 B.C. - 220 A.D.), Tang (618 - 906 A.D.), Song (960 - 1279 A.D.), and Yuan (1279-1368 A.D.).
    </p>

    <p>
        Chinese culture and thought was hugely influential in East Asia, much the same way that Greek culture influenced Europe. Mathematics was one of the six arts of Ancient China. Mastery of all six was required to be a <term>Junzi</term> or respectable person. Because of vast geographical distances, Chinese mathematics developed independently from Babylonian, Egyptian, and Greek mathematics. Certain results, like the Pythagorean Theorem were developed independently in both cultures.
    </p>

    <p>
       The most influential work of Ancient Chinese Mathematics is <em>The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art</em> or <em>The Nine Chapters</em> for short, which can be compared with Euclid's <em>Elements</em>. Unlike <em>The Elements</em> we do not know who wrote <em>The Nine Chapters</em> and likely it was compiled by multiple scholars over several generations from the 10th century to 2nd century BC. Because it is referenced by other Chinese sources, we know that it had to been written prior to 93 A.D.   
    </p>

    <p>
      Much like <em>The Elements</em>,  <em>The Nine Chapters</em> consists of a series of problems, followed by the solution and an explanation of the procedure that led to the solution. In all there are 246 problems in <em>The Nine Chapters</em>
    </p>
    
<p>
    Liu Hui, who used the method of exhaustion to determine the most accurate estimate of <m>\pi</m> at the time wrote a commentary on <em>The Nine Chapters</em> in 263, explaining the procedures in more detail as well as providing explanations for why the procedure yields the correct solution.  
</p>

<p>
  <em>The Nine Chapters</em> is divided into nine chapters that cover a variety of mathematical topics.
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 1 is called <term>Fangtian (Bounding Fields)</term>. It includes formulas for areas of various shapes such as triangles, rectangles, trapezoids, and circles. It also includes rules for counting rod manipulation. Liu Hui's commentary for this section includes his method for calculating <m>\pi</m> and his approximate value of <m>3.14159</m>
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 2 is called <term>Sumi (Millet and Rice)</term>. It involves the exchange of commodities at different rates, solving proportions and using fractions. 
</p>

<p>
  Chapter 3 is called <term>Cuifen (Proportional Distribution)</term>. It involves distribution of money and commodities at proportional rates as well as arithmetic and geometric sums.
</p>

<p>
  As an example, Chapter 3 Problem 3 states
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    There is a woman weaver who increases an [equal] amount each day. She weaves <m>5</m> chi on the first day and in a month <m>9</m> pi <m>3</m> zang. Find her increase each day.
  </p>
</blockquote>

<p>
  Chapter 4 is called <term>Shaoguang (Reducing Dimensions)</term>. It involves finding the diameter or side length of a shape given its area or volume and extractions of square roots and cube roots.
</p>

<p>
  Problem 12 of this chapter states
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>
    One has a square area of <m>55,225</m> pu. What is the side of the square?
  </p>
</blockquote>

<p>
  The answer is <m>\sqrt{55,255}</m> but the problem is to find the exact value. In <em>The Nine Chapters</em> this is done using the algebraic identity
  <md>
    (a+b+c)^2 = a^2+(2a+b)b + [2(a+b)+c]c
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  To extract the square root of <m>55,255</m> using the above identity one dissects a square of area <m>N = 55,225</m> as follows. This method can be used to extract the square root for any <m>N</m>
</p>

<p>
  Because <m>100^2 = 10,000 &lt; 55,255 &lt; 1,000,000 = 1,000^3</m> it follows that <m>\sqrt{N} = d_1d_2d_3</m>, i.e. a 3 digit number.
</p>

<p>
  To obtain the first digit <m>d_1</m> one seeks the largest square of side <m>S_1 = d_1 \cdot 10^2</m> satisfying <m>S_1^2 \leq N = 55,255</m>. Since <m>200^2 = 40,000 &lt; 90,000 = 300^2</m>, it follows that <m>d_1 = 2</m> 
</p>

<p>
  Removing the square with area <m>S_1^2</m> from the square of area <m>N</m> leaves a region with area <m>15,255</m>. The second digit <m>d_2</m> is found by selecting the largest value <m>S_2 = d_2 \cdot 10^1</m> with the property that
  <md>
    2S_1S_2+S_2^2 \leq N-S_1^2 = 15255
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  Before finding <m>d_2</m> let us explain the rationale for this condition. <m>2S_1S_2+s_2^2</m> is the area of two rectangles with sides <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> plus a square with side <m>S_2</m>. Adding this to the square of side <m>S_1</m> that we previously removed and together we have removed a square with side <m>S_1+S_2</m> from our original square with area <m>N</m>.
</p>

<p>
  To solve for <m>d_2</m> we notice that <m>2\cdot200\cdot 30 + 30^2 = 12,900</m> and <m>2\cdot200\cdot 40 + 40^2 = 17,600</m>. Thus <m>d_2 = 3</m>. Removing this area from the original square leaves an area of <m>2325</m>
</p>

<p>
  The third digit <m>d_3</m> is found by finding the largest value <m>S_3 = d_3 \cdot 10^0</m> for which
  <md>
    2(S_1+S_2)S_3 + S_3^2 \leq 2325.
  </md>
  
</p>

<p>
  The rationale for this choice is that <m>2(S_1+S_2)S_3 + S_3^2</m> is the area of two rectangles with sides <m>S_1+S_2</m> and <m>S_3</m> plus a square with side <m>S_3</m>. When added to the regions that were already removed, the total amount removed is a square with side length <m>S_1+S_2+S_3</m> proving the identity at the start of this problem.
</p>

<p>
  Note that <m>2(200+30)5+5^2 = 2325</m> exactly. Thus <m>d_3=5</m> and the square root of <m>55225</m> is <m>235</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Square root extraction doesn't result in a whole number answer unless you start with a perfect square. When this wasn't the case this method could be continued to produce a series of decimal places.
</p>
    
  </subsection>

  </section>